orical context, but by an attempt to understand it all in its complexity. "The play needs to be seen as what it was, to be understood as what it is."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aGreek drama (Tragedy)xHistory and criticism. 0aMythology, Greek, in literature. 4aAncient Archaeology. 4aAncient History. 4aEuropean literature. 4aMeno. 4aSophocles. 4aancient Greek history. 4aancient philosophy. 4aclassical antiquity. 4aclassical literature. 4aethics. 4ahistory of art. 4ahistory of philosophy. 4ahistory of the Americas. 4ahistory of western philosophy. 4ahistory. 4aliterature. 4amight. 4amoral philosophy. 4aphilosophy. 4apolitical philosophy. 4asocial philosophy. 4athe arts. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052004957440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052034177740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520341777423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520341777/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles